> That's not totally true. The name depend in which USB port you plug 
> the adapter. From the documentation of the Keyspan :
>
> "For example, a port named "USA28X9132" is referencing to the second 
> port on a Keyspan USB
>  Twin Serial Adapter (part number USA-28X). The numbers before the 
> last number refer to
>  location of that adapter on the USB bus. In this case, "913" is 
> reporting that the adapter is on USB
>  bus # 9, host hub port # 1


yup I suppose he/ she is using the same keyspan as me, so..........

>
> ------------------------------------------------------------------------
>
> and external hub port # 3."
>
> For that reason, I don't think it's a good idea to put a hard path in 
> the binary. I prefer the way that Martin did so you can pass the good 
> path whatever it is.
>
> I actually never use the comport object on os x. I'm using instead 
> pyext and a python script (with the pySerial module) to do the 
> communication. This way I was able to do a function to auto-discover 
> the port of the keyspan adapter whatever it is. It works very well.
